{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17530526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17530526"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:07:49+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:07:49+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14549"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14549","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14549"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.45,0.07,0.17,0.23]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7242"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101461"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7242","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7242"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14549"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83900"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"1487"},{"type":"tags","id":"3706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4659"},{"type":"tags","id":"4703"},{"type":"tags","id":"4705"},{"type":"tags","id":"4815"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17588"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35083"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35084"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101461","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101461"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a four-week history of a mildly sore throat. He denies any rhinorrhoea, cough or fevers and has tried taking an antihistamine with no relief. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.  He recalls attending his cousin\u0027s four-year old birthday party five weeks ago where many children had runny noses and coughing.  His vaccinations are up to date.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has had four sexual partners in the last six months, all male, and engages in receptive anal intercourse and performs and receives oral sex. He uses condoms when having anal intercourse. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Oropharyngeal examination reveals mild erythema of the pharynx with mild tonsillar enlargement. There is no tonsillar exudate or cervical lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA rapid strep test is negative. A throat swab is sent for nucleic acid amplification testing (NAAT).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following organisms is most likely responsible for this patient\u0027s symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Treponema pallidum","Chlamydia trachomatis","Haemophilus influenzae","Human immunodeficiency virus","Epstein-Barr virus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGiven the patient\u0027s history of unprotected oral sex with multiple male partners and the clinical presentation of persistent mild pharyngitis, \u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely causative organism in this case. While chlamydia is more commonly associated with genital infections, it can also cause pharyngitis. Pharyngeal infections are often asymptomatic or present with mild symptoms in the absence of typical coryzal symptoms. The mild symptoms persisting for three weeks, along with the absence of systemic symptoms, are consistent with chlamydial pharyngitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ETreponema pallidum\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E, the causative agent of syphilis, can cause pharyngeal chancres in primary syphilis. However, these are typically painless and accompanied by regional lymphadenopathy, which is not consistent with the presentation described.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E can cause pharyngitis, but it is less likely in this context of suspected sexually transmitted infection. \u003Cem\u003EH. influenzae\u003C/em\u003E pharyngitis typically presents as more acute in onset and may be associated with more systemic or other upper-respiratory tract symptoms, which are absent in this case. Whilst it is possible that the children at the party five weeks prior could have infected him at the time, it is unlikely to present with such a long history of symptoms and also  pharyngitis caused by \u003Cem\u003EH. influenzae\u003C/em\u003E would also be likely to have resolved by four weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHuman immunodeficiency virus \u003C/strong\u003E(HIV) seroconversion illness can present with pharyngitis, however the illness is usually about one week in duration. It typically occurs 2-4 weeks after initial infection and is usually accompanied by more severe systemic symptoms. These may include fever, fatigue, myalgia, arthralgia, lymphadenopathy, and sometimes a maculopapular rash. The absence of these systemic symptoms and the longer duration of symptoms make HIV seroconversion less likely in this case. However, given the patient\u0027s risk factors, HIV testing should still be considered as part of a comprehensive sexual health screen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEpstein-Barr virus\u003C/strong\u003E (EBV) causes infectious mononucleosis, which can present with pharyngitis. However, EBV infection typically causes more prominent systemic symptoms, significant lymphadenopathy, and often tonsillar exudate, which are not described in this case. The absence of fever and lymphadenopathy makes EBV less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe use of nucleic acid amplification testing (NAAT) on a throat swab is appropriate for detecting \u003Cem\u003EC. trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E in pharyngeal specimens. If the NAAT is positive for chlamydia, treatment typically would involve azithromycin or doxycycline. It\u0027s important to note that pharyngeal chlamydia can be asymptomatic, and screening of high-risk individuals, such as this patient with multiple unprotected sexual contacts, may be warranted even in the absence of symptoms.  This would be through oropharyngeal swab, first pass urine and anorectal swab for NAAT for gonorrhoea and chlamydia, as well as HIV and syphilis serology every 3 months, and hepatitis C, B and A screening for certain individuals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chlamydia trachomatis can cause pharyngitis, though it is less common than genital infections.","Chlamydia infections of the pharynx are frequently asymptomatic."],"references":["Khosropour CM, Soge OO, Golden MR, Hughes JP, Barbee LA. Incidence and Duration of Pharyngeal Chlamydia Among a Cohort of Men Who Have Sex With Men. Clin Infect Dis. 2022 Sep 14;75(5):875-881. doi: 10.1093/cid/ciab1022. PMID: 34893806; PMCID: PMC9477446. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC9477446/#:~:text=The%20prevalence%20of%20pharyngeal%20chlamydia%20we%20observed%20(1.4%25)%20is,1%2C%203%E2%80%935%5D.","Chlamydia - STI Guidelines Australia [Internet]. STI Guidelines Australia. 2024. Available from: https://sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/chlamydia/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83900"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14549"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"83900","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/83900"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"